Simulated example

Sreenath Madathil

April 8, 2018

Excess relative risk estimated using Odds ratios as suggested by David B. Richardson, Jay S. Kaufman,American Journal of Epidemiology,2010. Haitao Chu, Stephen R Cole proposed Bayesian approach to the model for two binary exposures.

Briefly the model is, \[odds_{i} = exp(\alpha)*(1+\beta_{1}*x_{1,i} + \beta_{2}*x_{2,i} + \beta_{3}*x_{1,i}*x_{2,i})\]
\[P(y_{i} = 1) = \frac{odds_{i}}{1+odds_{i}}\]

With the following constrains on parameters \[ \beta_{1} , \beta_{2} >= -1 \]
\[ \beta_{3} >= -(1+\beta_{1} + \beta_{2})\]

Simulating data

set.seed(4507907)

N <- 4000
x1 <- rbinom(N,1,0.5)
x2 <- rbinom(N,1,0.5)
x1x2 <- x1*x2

b <- c(-1,2,2,-1)

odds <- exp(b[1])*(1+ b[2]*x1 + b[3]*x2 + b[4]*x1x2)
p <- odds/(1+odds)

y <- rbinom(N,1,p)

dat = list(N=N, A=x1,B=x2, y=y)

Model specification in Stan

writeLines(readLines("linOdds.stan"))
## data{
##   int N;
##   vector[N] A;
##   vector[N] B;
##   int<lower=0, upper=1> y[N];
## }
## parameters{
##   real b0;
##   real<lower=-1> b1;
##   real<lower=-1> b2;
##   real<lower=-(1+b1+b2)> b3;
## }
## transformed parameters{
##   vector<lower=0>[N] odds;
##   vector<lower=0,upper=1>[N] pr;
##   
##   for(i in 1:N){
##     odds[i] = exp(b0)*(1+b1*A[i]+b2*B[i]+b3*A[i]*B[i]);
##     pr[i] = odds[i]/(1+odds[i]);
##   }
## }
## model{
##   b0 ~ normal(0,5);
##   b1 ~ normal(0,5);
##   b2 ~ normal(0,5);
##   b3 ~ normal(0,5);
##   
##   y ~ bernoulli(pr);
## }
## generated quantities{
##   vector[N] yrep;
##   for(i in 1:N){
##     yrep[i] = bernoulli_rng(pr[i]);
##   }
## }

Fitting model in stan

fit <- stan("linOdds.stan",
            data=dat, control = list(adapt_delta=0.99, max_treedepth=14))

Examining results

pairs(fit, pars=c("b0","b1","b2","b3"))

mcmc_trace(as.array(fit), pars=c("b0","b1","b2","b3"))

print(fit, pars=c("b0","b1","b2","b3"))

###Posterior predicitive check

yrep <- rstan::extract(fit, pars="yrep")
prep <- rstan::extract(fit, pars="pr")
odrep <- rstan::extract(fit, pars="odds")
ppc_bars(y,yrep$yrep[1:1000,])

ppc_dens_overlay(p,prep$pr[1:1000,])

ppc_intervals(odds, odrep$odds[1:1000,])

Fitting model in Jags

jD <- list(N=N, A=x1, B=x2, y=y, one=1)
js <- jags(data=dat, model.file ="linodds.jags", 
           parameters.to.save =c("b0","b1","b2","b3"),
           n.iter=10000, n.burnin =5000, parallel = TRUE,
           n.chains =4)

Finding

The 80% credible intervals of estimates include the true parameter values.
